05880nam a22009015i 9781487589127DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191980onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875891277 a10.3138/97814875891272doi  a(DE-B1597)513963  a(OCoLC)1091712941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aART0150402bisacsh04a700/.97104aThe Arts in Canada :bThe Last Fifty Years /ced. by William Keith, Ben-Z. Shek. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1980  a1 online resource (174 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcross the River and Out of the Trees -- tUn demi-siècle d'évolution culturelle au Québec -- tFiction in Canada - 1930 to 1980 -- tRomancier(s) québécois -- tNew World Northern: Of Poetry and Identity -- tPetit Testament -- tFifty Years of Theatre in Canada -- tLe Credo professionnel d'un homme de théâtre -- tWhen the Past Becomes History: The Half-Century in Non-Fiction Prose -- tLes Lettres québécoises depuis 1930 -- tFifty Years of Music in Canada? Good Lord, I Was There for All of Them! -- tFields of Force in Canadian Art, 1930 to 1980 -- tA Half-Century of UTQ -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this volume a baker's dozen of creative Canadians make personal responses to the state of the arts in Canada: Northrop Frye and Guy Rocher write on general cultural trends; Hugh MacLennan and Gérard Bessette on fiction; Ralph Gustafson and Michèle Lalonde on poetry; Robertson Davies and Gratien Gélinas on drama; George Woodcock and Jacques Allard on non-fiction prose; Godfrey Ridout on music, and Aba Bayefsky and Humphrey N. Milnes on art. The essays were written to mark the fiftieth anniversary of the University of Toronto Quarterly. The contributors were invited to discuss the changes, problems, challenges, and achievements in the arts in the last fifty years. Since all the authors had personal experience of at least a large section of the period surveyed, the editors welcomed personal reminiscence as well as description and assessment. The result is a varied group of essays in each of which the character of the individual artist is clearly evident; together, they provide a complex, many-faceted, lively, and living discussion of the cultural development of Canada. This anniversary collection of essays is a valuable and provocative source for courses in Canadian studies and for anyone interested in the development of the arts and humanities in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArtszCanada. 0aArts, Canadian. 7aART / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAllard, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayefsky, Aba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBessette, Gérard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Robertson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrye, Northrop, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGustafson, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGélinas, Gratien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeith, W.J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeith, William, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLalonde, Michèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLennan, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilnes, Humphrey N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRidout, Godfrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/